    {
      "sort": 300000,
      "name": "Combat",
      "type": "text",
      "_id": "KlmiZrvBGDx1E0BL",
      "system": {},
      "title": {
        "show": true,
        "level": 1
      },
      "image": {},
      "text": {
        "format": 1,
        "content": "<p>Combat is implemented in as much as attacks can be made, damage rolled and applied to Travellers, Creatures and Vehicles.</p><h2>Some Assumptions</h2><h3>Battle Maps</h3><p>Unlike some other game systems, Traveller doesn't require the use of battle maps in a game at all. Many players and GMs use Theatre of the Mind, using tokens on a scene only to track damage and list the available targets.</p><p>Some people struggle to imagine scenes in their head though, or just prefer to have a pretty map with well defined placement of characters and enemies. If using such a 'battle map', whether you use a grid or not is optional.</p><p>The MgT2e system doesn't enforce either, though there are some features that will make use of a scaled map if you are using one.</p><p>The general assumption is a 1.5m grid (square or hex), but again this is not enforced.</p><h4>Some Map Features</h4><h5>Making Attacks</h5><p>When making an attack, if you have a single token selected, then that token will be assumed to be the one making the attack.</p><p>If you have other tokens selected as targets (press 'T' when hovering over them), then these will be assumed as potential targets.</p><p>This allows the attack dialog to display the distance to each target, allowing you to more easily select the range of an attack.</p><h5>Grenades</h5><p>If the damage from a grenade, or other weapon with a blast radius, is dragged onto a map, then the blast radius will be automatically displayed on the map.</p><p>If the attack missed, then there is a world setting to allow for random displacement. However, this doesn't account for walls.</p><p></p>"
      },
      "video": {
